Author-Name:   Yi, Youjae
Title: 
 The Effects of Contextual Priming in Print Advertisements.

Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 215-22
Issue: 2
Volume: 17
Year: 1990
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 This study investigated one particular way that contextual materials can
 affect the processing of ambiguous product information in print ads. It
 was proposed that prior exposure to contextual factors can prime certain
 product attributes and subsequently increase the likelihood that consumers
 interpret product information in terms of these activated attributes,
 thereby affecting the evaluation of the adverised brand. Two experiments
 were conducted to test the hypothesis, and the results demonstrated that
 specific attributes relevant to evaluating the advertised brand varied in
 their acessibility as a function of the context and that these variations
 influenced brand attitudes.


