Author-Name:   Kirmani, Amna
Title: 
 The Effect of Perceived Advertising Costs on Brand Perceptions.

Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 160-71
Issue: 2
Volume: 17
Year: 1990
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 How, why, and when consumers use their perceptions of advertising costs
 as cues to a new brand's quality-related attributes is examined. It is
 proposed that consumers perceive advertising costs as deviations from
 expectations about typical costs in the product category. Perceived costs
 are hypothesized to affect brand perceptions in an inverted-U fashion with
 extemely high costs leading to negative perceptions. The level of
 involvement and informativeness of ad content moderate this relationship.
 An experiment in which subjects are exposed to an ad for a new product
 provides evidence for the proposed model.


